{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_2hayden_ver02/data/sn83045462/00280604987/1949052201/0576.xml":{"full_text":"Threat to Watch Industry\nSeen in Taritf Policy\n|y the Associated Press\nCHICAGO, May 21\u2014An Amer\nican watch manufacturer said to\nday that an inadequate, obsolete\nand unrealistic tariff\u201d on watch.\nImports is undermining the\nAmerican watch industry's ability\nto meet possible war emergency\ndemands.\nJames G. Shennan, president of\nthe Elgin National Watch Co.,\ntold the United Horological As\nsociation convention that \u2018\u2018tariffs\non watches were reduced in 1936\nby approximately 35 per cent.\n\u201cIn addition to this delitx#ate\nreduction, other factors have\ngreatly reduced the protection\nthat was Intended by the 1936\ntrade agreement with Switzerland,\nincluding devaluation of the\nSwiss franc and an almost 100\nper cent inflation since 1936.\u201d\nHe said labor rates in Switzer\nland were only about 40 per cent\nof wages in the United States.\n\u201cInasmuch as the cost of the\nwatch movement is almost entirely\nlabor, the American industry has\nnot been able to offset this great\ndisparity in labor costs despite\nextensive technological improve\nments and greater operating effi\nciency,\u201d he said.\n\"At the present time tne im\nporters\u2019 profit ratios are in some\ncases double those of the domes\ntic manufacturers.\u201d\n\"If war strikes again,\u201d he said,\n\"the American industry will be\nasked to supply not only a much\ngreater volume of military timing\ndevices than It produced in World\nWar II, but civilian timepieces as\nwell because It is not contem\nplated that any could be im\nported.\u201d\nCommodity Prices\nNEW YORK, May 21 (Ah.\u2014'The Asso\nciated Press Index of 36 important whole\nsale commodity prices this week declined\nto 155.16 on Friday from 166 44 a week\n\u2022arller.\nThe comparable Friday figure a year\nago was 189 32 The index hsse yesr of\n1923 equals 100.\nTwo of the six commodity groups in\nthe index were at new week-end lows\nfor the year\u2014industrials and textiles.\nPood and grains and cotton also declined,\nlivestock posted a moderate advance and\nBonferrous metals remained unchanged\nThe index, with comparable figures for\na week ago and a year ago. follows:\nWe* Year\nMay 20 Ago Ago\n85 commoditleg 155.18 155 44 189 32\nIndustrials_... *144 47 145.53 170 81\nPood _ 125.17 125.58 148.89\nLivestock 194.81 189.52 227.78\nGrains and eotton 180.70 1*2.54 233 85\nTextiles _ *129.31 131.18 181.13\nNonfer metals 156.97 168.97 172 69\n\u2022New 1949 low.\nThe index today declined to 155.14,\ncompared with 166 18 on Friday.\nNew York Cotton\nNEW YORK, May *1 (A\u2019t.\u2014'Trading In\ncotton futurec was the slowest in many\nmonths today. Pries changes were re\nstricted and most of ths dealings wars\noonflned to nearby dellvericc. The price\ntrend was toft.\nSpot houset cold nearby July with some\nOf the busineaa said to repreaent hedging.\nCotton dealerg were inclined to mark time,\npending freih developments In connection\nwith export aalea to Europe as well ai to\nChina.\nAnothar consideration was that the\ncritical period for cotton is coming to\nhand ana private advices from the South\nstated that virtually the entire belt is in\nneed for warm dry weather during thg\nnext three weeks.\nFutures closed 10 to 15 cents a bale\nlower than the previous close.\nOpen. High. Low. La\u00abt.\nJuly_ 82.58 82.69 82.58 82 59\nGet._ 29.07 2912 29.07 29.12\nDee._ 38.87 28 91 28 86 28 91\nMarch_ 28.78 28.79 28.78 28 78n\nMay __ 28.69 28.61 28.67 28 59n\nJuly_-\u2022 27.75b\nMiddling spot, 88.87b.\nb Nominal. __\nINSURED SAFETY\nplus liberal\nearnings are..\n<U rua* to you\n$4 you*\npoitman\nWe will gladly handle yoe'\nsavings account by mad\nno need for you to moke\ntrips in person to our office.\nPHEVY PHASE\nBUILDING LOAN\nASSOCIATION\n$94$ PlKMlO 4 H.\nCk'w, Ckmtt Mi. Ml. Utl\nWashington Stock Exchange\n.Report Compiled hr Exchange Official*.\nTRANSACTIONS ON W