ts com\nmon tnd low-medium. 20,50-2.1.00: odd\ngood hetfers. 2460-25.00; bulk medium\nand good 22.00-23 75: common down to\n20.00 and odd cutters as low as 18 50:\ngood cows mainly 20.00-21.00; odd head\nyoung cows, 21 50: common and me\ndium. 18 00-20.00: esnners tnd cutters.\n15.00- 17 50; good beef and sausage bulls.\n21.00: bulk good sausage. 21.00-21.00:\ncommon and medium grades. mainlv 18 no\n20.50: light cutters down to 17.00: h:gh\ngood and choice s'oeker and feeder steers\nand stock calves. 28.50-28.50: bulk supply\nmedium and tood grades. 474-867 pounds\n24.00- 26.00; low-medtum. 21.00; few\nsmall lots Inferior and common. 19.00\n22 60.\nrotnpgred last week: Oenerslly\n1 00-2.00. top 2.50 higher, most advance\non good tnd choice grades; week\u2019s top\nand closing top. 29.50; bulk good and\nchoice. 26.00-20.00; common and me\ndium. 11.00-26.00; culls largely 11.00\n21.00\nHogs, compared last week: Mostly 1.00,\ntop 1-26 higher; bulk good and chotct.\nISO-225 pounds trueked-in barrows and\ngllta. 20.25-20.50; 225-280 pounds, 10.75\n20.26: 260-300 pounds, 19.25-19.50; 300\n400 pounds, 17.60-18.25: oTer 400 pounds.\n17.25 down; 120-140 pounds, 17.50-17.76;\n140-160 pounds. 10.26-19.50; 160-180\npounds, 10.00-20.16; bulk under 225\npounds sailing at outside quotations; good\nand choice under 400-pound sows. 15.76\nto mostly 16.00; odd head under 300\npounds up to 17.00; good 400-460 pounds,\n14.75-16.00; heavier weights. 14.00 down.\nSheep, compared last week; Sprint Iambi\nfully 1.00 lower; slaughter awe* steady,\nacarce each day: good and choice spring\nlambs mainly 31.00-33.00' top, 83.00;\nlow-good down to 27.00: small lots com\nmon tnd medium. 23.00-26 00; good tnd\nchoice wooled ewst quoted to 12.50; same\ntrades shorn ewes mainly 11.00.\nGrata Markat.\nFlour\u2014Receipts. 9.558 100-pound sacks\nWheat\u2014Receipts. 76.151 bushels, ship\nments. 30.000 bushels, stocks. 1,249.563\nbushels. No. red winter garlicky, spot\ndomestic. 2 43: May, 2 43; No. 3 red\nwinter garlicky, spot. 2.39.\nCorn\u2014Receipts. 58.172 bushels; ship\nments. none: stocks. 621.086 bushels\nOats\u2014Receipts. 61,605 bushels; ship\nments. none; stocks, 180,343 bushels. No\nquotations\nBarlsy\u2014Receipts. nons: shipments,\nnone; itoeks, 327,414 bushels.\nRye\u2014Reoalpts. 45.718 bushels: ship\nments. nons; stocks, 858.763 bushels\nSoybeans\u2014Receipts. 1.878 bushels;\nshipments, 934 bushels; stocks, 862.730,\nbushels.\nMlllfeed\u2014Receipts. 389 tons.\nBatter sad Bags.\nBags\u2014Market about steady receipts\nlibersl: demand fair. Wholesale prices:\n4g large. 65-56: A mediums. 49-58; B\nlarge. 60-62; current receipt*, ungraded.\n46-48. few low at 44.\nBond Market Volume\nLowest for Saturday\nIn Nearly 35 Years\nr A\u00bb\u00bboc*o*\u00ab\u00ab\nNEW YORK. May 21\u2014The bond\nmarket had lta aiowest Saturday\nm almost 35 jteara today as Wall\nStreet prematurely began Its an\nnual Saturday summer closings.\nThe volume w as $542 000, com\npared with last week* $1 420.000.\nIt was the lowest since December\n26. 1914 when the volume was\nS462 000\nIn 1914, the New York market\nclosed on July 31 and reopened in\nNovember with trading in bonds\nunder restrictions.\nThe market followed a narrow\npath today with prices mixed.\nThere were few issues that changed\nmore than small fractions.\nContrary to the trend in the dull\nmarket was the sale of one bond\nof Public Service Electric Gas 8s\nwhich moved up 5 points to 220.\nThis issue, highest priced on the\nexchange and carrying the largest\ncoupon, is rarely traded.\nAmerican Tobacco 3s advanced\n4 at 1037g sfhd New Haven income\n44s were up a similar figure at\n384\nCommonwealth Edison 3s fell\n3s to 1043b and Lehigh Valley\nHudson Terminal 5s dropped a\npoint to 614\nThere was no trading in United\nStates Government issues. Brazil\nian issues moved ahead fractions\nin a dull foreign dollar list.\nSaturday Trading to ina.\nThis is the last Saturday of\ntrading until October 1.\nThe week's bond market record\nshowed traders had little change\nof viewpoint regarding the uncer\ntain business outlook and the\nlabor picture.\nWith many traders taking side\nline positions, the market accom\nplished little of consequence dur\ning the six-day session. In a great\nmajority of cases today s closing\nprices were at very little variance\nfrom last Saturday's closing.\nUnited States Treasury bonds\nshowed some improvement in\nover-the-counter trading during\nthe week. This was attributed\nlargely to the formal announce\nment by the Treasury that it would\noffer only one-year. U\u00ab per cent\ncertificates for more than $5,000,\n000.000 in bonds and other certifi\ncates being redeemed next month.\nBankers had hoped and half\nexpected. the Treasury would re\ndeem at least a portion of the\nsecurities with five-year notes\npaying higher interest.\n17. 8. Bonds in Demand.\nThis hope resulted In recent\nselling in Government bonds, but\nwhen the Treasury indicated no\nnotes would be issued, banks re\nsumed bond buying.\nAs an instance of the re-estab\nlished demand for long-term Gov\nernment securities, the bank eligi\nble 2 !s of September, 1972-1967.\npicked up 5 32 of a point during\nthe week, closing Friday at a bid\nprice of 103 12/32.\nThe ready response to some\nstock issues offered for sale this\nweek knocked one prop from un\nder the current argument that one\ntrouble with American business is\na lack of equity capital.\nInvestment bankers offered 800,\n000 shares of Southern California\nEdison Co. common stock at 32Vi\na share and 80.000 shares of $4.50\ncumulative preferred stock of\nUnited Biscuit Co. at $103.50 a\nshare.\nBoth issues quickly were over\nsubscribed.\nIn addition, a secondary offering\nof 18.000 shares of Great Atlantic\nPacific Tea Co. common at 109*4\na share was bought out immedi\nately.\nFinancing to Decrease.\nCorporate debt financing will be\nreduced to a mere trickle next\nweek. The only offerings in sight\nare- two issues of railroad equip\nment trust certificates\u2014$3,150,000\nwhich the Delaware, Lackawanna\nSi Western is offering on Wednes\nday and $2,550,000 which the\nM-K-T will market on Tuesday.\nThe field of tax-exempt financ\ning has an active week scheduled.\nThe entrance of additional \"new\nmoney\u201d will give dealers plenty of\nwork in trying to dispose of the\nunsold inventories of State, munic\nipal and county obligations, which\nat one point this week totaled a\nrecord $178,560,000. The figure\nlater was worked down to around\n$170,000,000\nNext week\u2019s tax-exempt offer\nings include $26,687,000 in tempo\nrary loan notes by the New York\nCity Housing Authority to be sold\nWednesday and $2,500,000 in vet\nerans' bonds by the State of Ohio,\nalso on Wednesday.\nAlthough transparency is the\ndistinguishing characteristic of\nfine American hand-made glass\nware, it is made almost entirely\nfrom opaque materials.\nBusiness Trends for Week\n\u2022y the Associated Pros\nThe following figure# tell the buitneu and financial operating start In the latest\nweek, with comparisons with the preceding week and a year ago\nLatest Weak. Free Week. Tear Ago\nSteel production (per cent of capacity) \u00bb5.6\nFreight carloadings _ 771..36 768.33 848 846\nAutomobile production (unite)- 115.987 11P 634 Jl 138\nft coal production (toni) 11.040.000 11 200.000 1J-9*5-2JS\nde oil production (barrel*)_ 4.889.3*0 4.896.7*0 5 472 800\nerring awards _9157 773.000 9130.991.000 $82 ,28.000\nsales (sham) _ 4,381 082 4.052.470 13 372.338\nsales (par value) _- $15.635.250 914.898.750 928.684 800\nBusiness failures (number) _ 171 19-' _ 100\n(Final thrae ciphers emitted In following\nSSrt5iSS5i* iiWffi i*S\u00ae8i\nftSSSS \u00abuHHi 888 lftfg 888 fflfm\nExcess reserve* ___ 11.080.000 $880,000 $330,000\nTreasury gold stock_ $24 338.000 914.335.000 9*3 245.000\nBrokers' loans _ fl.460.noo $1.038 000 $650,000\nMoney, ta fraJuisgs_ 927.382.000 927 452.000 9J7.690.000\nOwn Yoar\nOwi Norm!\nDIRECT\nREDUCTION LOA